WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:03.640
And to some degree, we've also talked about access control.

00:03.640 --> 00:09.520
What's left to discuss now are integrity controls and also digital signatures.

00:09.520 --> 00:12.360
And you'll see that the two are really related to each other.

00:12.360 --> 00:19.280
In fact, addressing digital signatures which address non-repudiation requires us to take

00:19.280 --> 00:21.120
care of integrity first.

00:21.120 --> 00:25.200
So what we're going to talk about in this section are what are called message integrity

00:25.200 --> 00:28.840
controls that cryptography can help for us.

00:28.840 --> 00:35.000
Now if you'll remember, what integrity means from a cryptography perspective is if I send

00:35.000 --> 00:41.080
you a message, what I need to do is I need to do something with that message first from

00:41.080 --> 00:47.560
an integrity perspective or from a cryptography perspective to come up with the representation

00:47.560 --> 00:50.000
of the message that I'm sending you.

00:50.000 --> 00:54.920
And then what I do is I send you the message, but I also send you that representation along

00:54.920 --> 00:56.000
with it.

00:56.000 --> 01:01.520
So that when you receive the message and the representation, you will take just the

01:01.520 --> 01:09.360
message, put it through the same integrity algorithm that I did to come up with a representation

01:09.360 --> 01:11.160
of what you've received.

01:11.160 --> 01:14.440
And then you will compare that with the one that I sent you.

01:14.440 --> 01:18.920
And if the two values match, it means that nothing happened along the way.

01:18.920 --> 01:24.640
The whole purpose of message integrity controls is to identify when something happens along

01:24.640 --> 01:25.640
the way.

01:25.640 --> 01:31.360
And what could happen along the way could be due to someone intentionally changing it

01:31.360 --> 01:33.920
or maybe errors happened along the way.

01:33.920 --> 01:39.480
But regardless of what causes the change, we want to be able to identify when it gets

01:39.480 --> 01:40.480
to you.

01:40.480 --> 01:43.960
So that's what all message integrity controls do.

01:43.960 --> 01:49.120
And what they rely on are integrity controls that focus on cryptography.

01:49.120 --> 01:51.600
It's called one way encryption.

01:51.600 --> 01:57.240
One way encryption takes a message or a data of any length, for example.

01:57.240 --> 02:04.760
And we'll always produce a small representation of the entire thing, which can be useful in

02:04.760 --> 02:09.640
identifying, for example, changes when we send or we store something.

02:09.640 --> 02:13.160
So the idea of integrity controls is pretty simple.

02:13.160 --> 02:17.360
And I'm going to illustrate that by using this example here.

02:17.360 --> 02:22.520
Let's say this is the data that I want to send you.

02:22.520 --> 02:28.400
The whole purpose of integrity controls is to take the entire thing, do something to it

02:28.400 --> 02:33.400
mathematically to come up with the representation of the entire thing.

02:33.400 --> 02:37.680
But by using a small value, something that is really small.

02:37.680 --> 02:42.480
And I think if you look at this, you can probably come up with a way that we can, for example,

02:42.480 --> 02:47.520
look at this entire data to come up with the one digit number that really represents

02:47.520 --> 02:48.520
the entire thing.

02:48.520 --> 02:56.320
In fact, if we look at this, if we add all of the digits and use that as the representation,

02:56.320 --> 02:58.080
we come up with a number nine.

02:58.080 --> 03:03.760
But the number nine is a one digit number that really represents the entire message.

03:03.760 --> 03:10.760
And so what I do now is I send you this, the message, but I also send you this representation.

03:10.760 --> 03:17.960
And by the way, this representation is usually referred to as a digest or a message digest.

03:17.960 --> 03:21.040
Both I think is what you might see on the exam.

03:21.040 --> 03:26.520
But it is that representation, that small representation of the entire message.

03:26.520 --> 03:30.280
So I send you the message and the digest along with it.

03:30.280 --> 03:35.800
So let's say that it gets to you and nothing happened along the way.

03:35.800 --> 03:42.400
So I sent you this and the nine, you ended up getting the exact same thing and the nine.

03:42.400 --> 03:47.000
So what you do now is you're going to take what you've received and put it through the

03:47.000 --> 03:50.080
same mathematical process that I did.

03:50.080 --> 03:52.280
So you're going to add up the digits.

03:52.280 --> 03:56.000
You're going to get the number nine and then you're going to compare it to the one that

03:56.000 --> 03:57.000
I sent you.

03:57.000 --> 04:01.560
And if the two values match, it means that nothing happened along the way.

04:01.560 --> 04:06.040
Because if something had happened along the way, let's say the first digit changed.

04:06.040 --> 04:10.760
For example, let's say that I sent you this and the nine, but the first digit changed

04:10.760 --> 04:12.400
to a two, let's say.

04:12.400 --> 04:17.080
So I sent you this, you end up getting this.

04:17.080 --> 04:21.800
When you add up the digits here, you're going to get a different value than the one that

04:21.800 --> 04:23.040
I sent you.

04:23.040 --> 04:27.860
And so when you compare those two values, you're going to say, oh, the two values do not

04:27.860 --> 04:28.860
match.

04:28.860 --> 04:31.060
Digests do not match.

04:31.060 --> 04:34.820
You're going to call me back and say, John, please re-send the information something

04:34.820 --> 04:36.620
happened along the way.

04:36.620 --> 04:41.660
We've been able to identify integrity problems in transmission.

04:41.660 --> 04:46.420
That's what the whole point of integrity controls really are to identify when something

04:46.420 --> 04:50.380
changes, either purposely or unintentionally.

04:50.380 --> 04:54.500
But regardless of what caused the change, we've been able to identify it.

04:54.500 --> 04:59.060
Now one more thing to illustrate this, and that is to illustrate here.

04:59.060 --> 05:03.940
And that is that our method of doing this is not good enough, right?

05:03.940 --> 05:10.420
We need to use better math, for example, that is more sensitive to very small bit changes.

05:10.420 --> 05:14.660
You obviously want these mathematical processes to be very sensitive.

05:14.660 --> 05:19.220
Because in our case, let's say the first two digits changed.

05:19.220 --> 05:27.780
Let's say I sent you this and the nine, but you end up getting this and the nine.

05:27.780 --> 05:33.180
When you add up the digits here, you're going to get the same number, the same digest that

05:33.180 --> 05:34.180
I sent.

05:34.180 --> 05:37.740
But the two messages are actually different, aren't they?

05:37.740 --> 05:44.060
And so because our mathematical process here is not good enough, then it's not able

05:44.060 --> 05:47.500
to identify everything that could happen to your data.

05:47.500 --> 05:51.100
So you want these methods to be much better than what we're using here.

05:51.100 --> 05:57.820
In fact, what we have illustrated here, when you have two different messages that produce

05:57.820 --> 06:05.540
the same digest, that is what is referred to as a collision in cryptography.

06:05.540 --> 06:11.060
And the word collision actually can only be in reference to hashing algorithms or integrity

06:11.060 --> 06:12.060
controls.

06:12.060 --> 06:16.180
We cannot use that word anywhere else in cryptography.

06:16.180 --> 06:23.260
So this is basically the function that all message integrity controls provide for us.

06:23.260 --> 06:27.620
And if we turn to the next slide here, you're going to see that there are a whole bunch

06:27.620 --> 06:31.260
of different integrity controls that exist out there.

06:31.260 --> 06:33.180
And it's represented on your slide here.

06:33.180 --> 06:35.820
So for example, we have parity protection.

06:35.820 --> 06:37.740
We have hashing functions.

06:37.740 --> 06:39.500
We have check sums.

06:39.500 --> 06:41.500
We have CRC checks.

06:41.500 --> 06:44.060
We have message authentication codes.

06:44.060 --> 06:46.340
What's the difference between all of them?

06:46.340 --> 06:53.220
Well, the difference is in the math that they use to come up with the number or that small

06:53.220 --> 06:58.140
representation that really represents the data itself.

06:58.140 --> 07:01.540
Some use better math than others, all right?

07:01.540 --> 07:02.540
Some are very simple.

07:02.540 --> 07:05.860
Like for example, CRC checks use very simple math.

07:05.860 --> 07:09.780
So do check sums and message authentication codes.

07:09.780 --> 07:15.860
The ones that use the best math are the ones that we're going to focus on from this point

07:15.860 --> 07:16.860
on.

07:16.860 --> 07:20.020
And they are called hashing algorithms.

07:20.020 --> 07:26.380
And hashing algorithms are things like, and I'm sure you've heard of these, MD5 and

07:26.380 --> 07:29.020
Shaw for example.

07:29.020 --> 07:33.940
So the hashing algorithms are the ones that use the best math because we want them to be

07:34.020 --> 07:42.540
very sensitive to small bit changes because these will take any size or arbitrary length input

07:42.540 --> 07:48.300
and always produce a digest that is very small, but you want them to be able to identify

07:48.300 --> 07:50.500
very small bit changes.

07:50.500 --> 07:56.100
And those are what we call hashing algorithms like MD5 and Shaw 1.

07:56.100 --> 08:00.820
So hashing functions is sometimes what they're also called, but hashing algorithms I think

08:00.820 --> 08:05.580
is pretty standard as far as the industry is concerned.

08:05.580 --> 08:10.020
And what they do and here's what you need to remember about hashing algorithms is that

08:10.020 --> 08:13.380
they will always take a message of any length.

08:13.380 --> 08:19.500
It doesn't matter if it's one word, one email for example, or your entire hard drive.

08:19.500 --> 08:26.180
They take arbitrary length input and always produce a fixed length digest.

08:26.180 --> 08:30.780
And so if we focus on the two that are very important here, you'll know that MD5

08:30.780 --> 08:36.540
will always produce a 128 bit digest for example.

08:36.540 --> 08:41.260
Shaw will always produce a 160 bit digest.

08:41.260 --> 08:45.340
So at least Shaw 1, you'll see that there's different versions of Shaw that we're going

08:45.340 --> 08:47.340
to talk about coming up here.

08:47.340 --> 08:54.100
And so again, if the message is very large, it will always also produce a fixed sized

08:54.100 --> 08:55.500
result.

08:55.500 --> 09:00.420
And in fact, it doesn't matter what you put into it, it will always produce that fixed

09:00.420 --> 09:05.020
size result, which is referred to as the digest itself.

09:05.020 --> 09:10.060
Now for these, to be really good, and that's why they are really good, we've already said

09:10.060 --> 09:12.700
that they do use the best math.

09:12.700 --> 09:17.380
But that also means that the way that these hashing algorithms have been developed is that

09:17.380 --> 09:22.220
they address some really important characteristics and elements that make them really good.

09:22.220 --> 09:24.980
For example, they have to be one way.

09:24.980 --> 09:29.700
And what they mean by one way is that we can take a message of any length and produce

09:29.780 --> 09:35.300
that digest, but nobody can take that digest and work backwards to be able to disclose,

09:35.300 --> 09:39.540
for example, what the message look like, they can only go one way.

09:39.540 --> 09:46.220
Deterministic means that if you take the same message twice and you hash it using the

09:46.220 --> 09:51.780
exact same hashing algorithm, it will always produce the same digest, no matter how many

09:51.780 --> 09:53.140
times you do it.

09:53.140 --> 09:58.020
It will always produce the same digest, and that's obviously very important.

09:58.020 --> 10:03.060
These hashing algorithms also need to look at the entire message in order to come up

10:03.060 --> 10:08.260
with that digest, because if they don't, the part that they don't look at can change

10:08.260 --> 10:13.380
and you'd never be able to identify messages that have changed, for example.

10:13.380 --> 10:16.540
Uniformly distributed simply means that they're available everywhere.

10:16.540 --> 10:21.740
There's a lot of crypto systems that have these hashing algorithms built in that will

10:21.740 --> 10:26.220
allow any two parties, for example, to address integrity very easily.

10:26.220 --> 10:32.300
They are widely accessible and available for all kinds of different applications.

10:32.300 --> 10:38.860
As we illustrated before, collisions are not good in integrity controls.

10:38.860 --> 10:44.580
These hashing algorithms do resist collisions really well, although the opportunity for

10:44.580 --> 10:48.420
collisions will never totally go away.

10:48.420 --> 10:52.620
The experts in this industry tell us that because you're always taking a message of any

10:52.700 --> 10:58.180
length and always producing something that is very small, the opportunity for collisions

10:58.180 --> 11:04.220
will always be possible, but you want these to resist that as much as possible.

11:04.220 --> 11:09.220
The ones that are the use the most often and are the most popular is what you see on

11:09.220 --> 11:10.740
this slide.

11:10.740 --> 11:17.740
By far, MD5 is the most commonly used hashing algorithm out there.

11:17.740 --> 11:26.300
There's other versions of it, for example, MD2, MD4, MD5 came along, it's like the historical

11:26.300 --> 11:27.580
evolution of these.

11:27.580 --> 11:33.820
We also have MD6 today, although MD5 is still the standard for a lot of applications.

11:33.820 --> 11:41.100
Shaw1, as we said before, is also very popular, produces a digest of 160 bits and you may

11:41.100 --> 11:47.900
have to remember the size of the digest that is produced by each of these hashing algorithms.

11:47.900 --> 11:54.100
There is what we call Shaw3, which has become the standard for many applications that require

11:54.100 --> 12:00.780
a lot more security and that includes a number of versions of the Shaw algorithm and some

12:00.780 --> 12:08.340
of them are Shaw256, Shaw384, Shaw512, for example, that number indicates the size

12:08.420 --> 12:13.620
of the digest that is being produced by that particular version of Shaw.

12:13.620 --> 12:18.940
One of the questions that you might see somewhere is what's the advantage of using a longer

12:18.940 --> 12:24.620
digest and the obvious answer to that is that you will have less collisions.

12:24.620 --> 12:29.580
The longer the digest, the less opportunity for collisions and that's why some of these

12:29.580 --> 12:31.060
are very popular.

12:31.060 --> 12:36.020
In fact, a collision is what we're trying to show you here on this slide where you have

12:36.020 --> 12:42.260
two different messages that produce the exact same digest and that's what we'd refer

12:42.260 --> 12:50.540
to as collision and good hashing algorithms will and should resist that as much as possible,

12:50.540 --> 12:57.460
especially these ones and the better versions of Shaw that are collected within that Shaw3

12:57.460 --> 13:00.180
algorithm that we talk about there.

13:00.180 --> 13:04.700
Now, one of the things that you may see on the exam that we're going to talk about in

13:04.700 --> 13:09.780
more detail later is something called the birthday paradox that relates to something

13:09.780 --> 13:12.460
called the birthday attack.

13:12.460 --> 13:18.660
You need to remember that the birthday attack is a attack that people have come up with

13:18.660 --> 13:24.580
against hashing algorithms like MD5 and Shaw1, for example.

13:24.580 --> 13:30.700
What they try and do is they try and use the math that the birthday paradox uses and

13:30.700 --> 13:34.660
if you know anything about this, it goes something like this.

13:35.660 --> 13:40.380
If you have a room of 23 people, that's the magic number.

13:40.380 --> 13:45.660
The chance that two of those people, any two of those people share the same birthday is

13:45.660 --> 13:52.300
actually greater than 50% at that point and as you start adding more people in the room,

13:52.300 --> 13:57.860
the opportunity or the probability that two people share the same birthday in that room

13:57.860 --> 14:04.620
will actually grow exponentially to the point where you only need 60 people in a room

14:05.180 --> 14:11.740
to have the probability be 99% that any two of those people in that room share the same

14:11.740 --> 14:12.740
birthday.

14:12.740 --> 14:16.540
By birthday, we mean month and day, not year.

14:16.540 --> 14:18.860
This is referred to as the birthday paradox.

14:18.860 --> 14:22.860
You can Google it and there's all kinds of videos that have been made about this pretty

14:22.860 --> 14:24.540
cool math.

14:24.540 --> 14:30.860
The bottom line here is that there is a specific attack against hashing algorithms that people

14:30.860 --> 14:38.100
have devised that basically uses the same math to find, guess what, different messages

14:38.100 --> 14:42.100
that produce the same digest, which is a collision.

14:42.100 --> 14:48.500
So what you need to remember as far as this is concerned, just remember birthday attack,

14:48.500 --> 14:54.180
hashing algorithms, collisions, if you see any one of those, think of the others and it

14:54.180 --> 14:56.980
should give you the answer to the exam question.

14:56.980 --> 15:02.140
But the math called the birthday attack is something that uses the birthday paradox math

15:02.140 --> 15:05.700
to be able to try and find collisions with different messages.

